    <summary>The Bitcoin community is currently engaged in a debate about how best to address scalability issues. One of the main problems is the cost of validation, which makes it difficult to construct short proofs. Currently, there is no mechanism for compensating validators, and even full validators that go offline for a short period of time take a while to catch up to the network. The community has discussed hard-forking to remove the 1MB limit on block size, but this could result in a severe market price correction. Instead, some have proposed a soft-forkable extension-block approach or a merge-mining solution where a forked Bitcoin with no block size limit could be mined alongside the original.There is also ongoing discussion about centralized services versus decentralized approaches in the block size debate. The industry trend of using web2.0 technology in wallets/services is due to a generation of developers who see no alternatives, but efforts like Lighthouse are trying to show people that they can blend traditional client-side development with the good bits of the web. Companies need to invest in the integration and coding implied to improve their products' scalability. Despite the challenges, several initiatives like Lightning and StrawPay are working towards more scalable solutions. However, the debate continues about whether raising the block size limit is enough or if more algorithmic improvements are needed. The community acknowledges the importance of decentralization and the need to avoid central points of failure.Another issue with Bitcoin scalability is the validation cost, not the complexity of block validation. Suggestions have been made for a hard-fork to remove the 1MB limit, but others propose a soft-forkable extension-block approach or merge-mining solution to allow both versions to coexist. The conversation also includes discussions about BIP100 and mining votes, paying bitcoins to future miners, layering models for improving algorithmic complexity, and links to related proposals.The Bitcoin development community is engaged in a debate over the block size limit, with some advocating for an increase while others argue that it should remain at 1MB. The option of hard-forking Bitcoin to remove the block size restriction has been proposed, but concerns remain about what will happen to the original 1MB limited Bitcoin. One solution suggested is to hard-fork and merge-mine, allowing both versions to exist and mining power to remain undivided. StrawPay is developing a cheap and secure micropayments system, but hasn't released any details publicly.The article also discusses the issue of outsourcing to third-party services and the argument against it. The author explains that the only way to achieve a trustless querying of the UTXO set is to be a full node and download all transactions, but even then, there is still room for error. Querying multiple peers and cross-referencing their answers is a compromise that provides more decentralization and robustness. However, this approach is not favored in Bitcoin Core, and developers are discouraged from trying it. Therefore, outsourcing to trusted services seems like an easier option.In conclusion, the Bitcoin community is actively seeking solutions to address scalability issues, including increasing the block size limit, implementing merge-mining, and creating better data structures and algorithms. There is ongoing debate about the best approach, with some arguing for incremental solutions rather than changing parameters that could break decentralization security. The community recognizes the importance of decentralization and the need to avoid central points of failure. Companies need to invest in improving their products' scalability, and efforts are being made to show that traditional client-side development can be blended with web2.0 technology. Despite the challenges, several initiatives like Lightning and StrawPay are working towards more scalable solutions.</summary>
